.START 

The bankruptcy judge overseeing the L.J. Hooker Corp. filing under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code approved and signed the order authorizing the sale of Parisian Inc., a Southeast department store chain, to its management. 

The price was $31 million plus other considerations.
Parisian was represented by Ocean Capital Corp., a New York investment banking company. 

L.J. Hooker is the U.S. subsidiary of Hooker Corp., the Australian property developer that is being managed by a court-appointed liquidator. 

Under Chapter 11, a company continues to operate but has court protection against creditors' lawsuits while it tries to work out a plan for paying its debts. 

